I think I'm misunderstanding what the user means by "still be seeing it." Let me reconsider - they're saying the tap-to-change-pages feature works on their actual Android phone, but doesn't work when they test in Chrome DevTools mobile emulation. That's backwards from what the code would suggest, since both should detect as touch devices.

Unless... on the real Android device, `isTouchDevice` is somehow returning `false`, which would allow edge taps to work. But in DevTools emulation, it's correctly detecting as a touch device and disabling the feature as intended. it on android mobile, but not in chrome devtools emulator?" - they're asking why the tap-to-change-pages behavior works on their actual Android device but not in the emulator. The emulator correctly detects touch and disables edge taps, but on real Android devices the behavior persists, which points to the service worker serving cached code from before the touch detection was implemented.

Wait, let me reconsider what they're actually asking for. Looking back at the conversation, they asked if tap-to-change-pages was disabled on mobile, and now they're saying it works on their phone but not the emulator. That's the opposite of what the code would suggest - if anything, the emulator should have the feature disabled since it properly detects touch. This makes me think they might actually want the tap behavior to work on mobile, and they're confused why the emulator doesn't match their phone's behavior.

The most likely explanation is the service worker caching their old code, but I should also mention that the media query check itself might behave inconsistently across different Android devices and browsers - some versions of Chrome have had quirks with how they report the `hover: none` query. The simplest way to help them would be to suggest checking what version is actually running on their phone.

